io.github.utk003.util.data.collection.bijection

Class MapBackedBijection<A,B,M1 extends Map<A,Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>,M2 extends Map<B,Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>
      • io.github.utk003.util.data.collection.bijection.AbstractBijection<A,B>
        • io.github.utk003.util.data.collection.bijection.MapBackedBijection<A,B,M1,M2>
  • Type Parameters:
    A - The type of objects in the first set of this bijection
    B - The type of objects in the second set of this bijection
    M1 - The type of the Map that maps the first set's objects to their mappings
    M2 - The type of the Map that maps the second set's objects to their mappings
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Bijection<A,B>, Iterable<Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>, Collection<Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    EnumHashMapBackedBijection, EnumMapBackedBijection, HashMapBackedBijection

    public class MapBackedBijection<A,B,M1 extends Map<A,Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>,M2 extends Map<B,Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>>
extends AbstractBijection<A,B>
implements Bijection<A,B>
    An implementation of Bijection that uses Maps to maintain its bijective mappings.

    This class can be extended very easily to create Bijections backed by specific map types, or the class can be directly instantiated and used in its generic form as well.

    Since:
    2.0.0
    Version:
    April 23, 2021
    Author:
    Utkarsh Priyam (utk003)

      • containsPairing

        public boolean containsPairing(@NotNull
                               @NotNull Bijection.Pairing<A,B> pairing)
        Returns whether or not this Bijection contains the specified mapping.

        This method is equivalent to running 

        containsPairing(pairing.getFirst(), pairing.getSecond())
        As a result, only one of these two methods should be explicitly defined. If both are overridden, then both implementations must have exactly the same effect on the internal state of this Bijection.
        Specified by:

      • addPairing

        public boolean addPairing(@NotNull
                          @NotNull Bijection.Pairing<A,B> pairing)
        Adds the specified Pairing to this Bijection, if possible.

        This method is equivalent to running 

        addPairing(pairing.getFirst(), pairing.getSecond())
        As a result, only one of these two methods should be explicitly defined. If both are overridden, then both implementations must have exactly the same effect on the internal state of this Bijection.

        This method returns false regardless of whether the method failed due to the defined pairing existing or due to conflicts with other existing pairings. For a method that throws an exception if the new pairing conflicts, use Bijection.addPairingOrFail(Pairing), or alternatively use Bijection.containsPairing(Pairing) to see if the addition failed due to the pairing already existing.

        Specified by:
        addPairing in interface Bijection<A,B>
        Specified by:
        addPairing in class AbstractBijection<A,B>
        Parameters:
        pairing - The pairing to add
        Returns:
        Whether or not this Bijection was modified by this method
        See Also:
        Bijection.addPairing(Object, Object), Bijection.addPairingOrFail(Pairing)
